{
  "lists": [
    {
      "level": "A1",
      "title": "Turkish A1 Grammar Path",
      "description": "A1 grammar in the order of the standard CEFR-aligned Turkish curricula (Yedi İklim / İstanbul): 'to be' suffixes and demonstratives first, then plural, questions, existence, possession, cases, and the present continuous."
    },
    {
      "level": "A2",
      "title": "Turkish A2 Grammar Path",
      "description": "The core suffix machine: witnessed past, future, dative/ablative/genitive, the aorist, ability, comparison, postpositions."
    },
    {
      "level": "B1",
      "title": "Turkish B1 Grammar Path",
      "description": "Nuance and combination: evidential -miş, necessity, conditionals, verbal nouns, gibi/kadar, -ken."
    },
    {
      "level": "B2",
      "title": "Turkish B2 Grammar Path",
      "description": "Complex sentences the Turkish way: -en/-dik participles, passive, causative, reported speech, converbs."
    },
    {
      "level": "C1",
      "title": "Turkish C1 Grammar Path",
      "description": "Advanced clause-linking: -dikçe, -meden, reflexive/reciprocal voice, -diği için."
    },
    {
      "level": "C2",
      "title": "Turkish C2 Grammar Path",
      "description": "Register and rhetoric: formal -mekte, -mış gibi, -eceğine."
    }
  ],
  "points": [
    {
      "title": "Personal pronouns and 'to be' (-(y)im, -sin…)",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Introduce yourself and others",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 1,
      "explanation": "Turkish has no separate verb 'to be' in the present — a personal suffix attaches straight to the noun or adjective: öğrenci-yim (I am a student), öğretmen-sin (you are a teacher), o doktor (he/she is a doctor — third person takes no suffix). The suffix vowel follows vowel harmony, and -y- is inserted after a vowel: iyi-yim (I'm fine).",
      "culture_note": "Dropping the pronoun is normal — 'Öğrenciyim' alone is a complete, natural sentence. The pronoun is added for contrast or emphasis.",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Turkish grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turkish_grammar"
        },
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Turkish copula",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turkish_copula"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "Ben {{answer}}.",
          "answer": "öğrenciyim",
          "translation": "I am a student.",
          "hint": "öğrenci + -(y)im",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Sen {{answer}}.",
          "answer": "öğretmensin",
          "translation": "You are a teacher.",
          "hint": "öğretmen + -sin",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Demonstratives (bu, şu, o)",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Point things out",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 2,
      "explanation": "Three distances: bu (this, near me), şu (that, a bit away / something I'm pointing at), o (that, over there — also 'he/she/it'). With a noun they work like English: bu kitap (this book), o ev (that house).",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Turkish grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turkish_grammar"
        },
        {
          "title": "Wiktionary: bu (Turkish)",
          "url": "https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/bu#Turkish"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} bir kitap.",
          "answer": "Bu",
          "translation": "This is a book.",
          "hint": "near the speaker",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} bir ev.",
          "answer": "O",
          "translation": "That (over there) is a house.",
          "hint": "far from both speakers",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Plural (-ler / -lar)",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Talk about more than one",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 3,
      "explanation": "Form the plural by adding -ler after front vowels and -lar after back vowels. Important exception: after a number, the noun stays singular — üç kitap ('three books'), never üç kitaplar.",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Turkish grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turkish_grammar"
        },
        {
