    {
      "title": "Locative case (-de / -da)",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Say where something is",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 5,
      "explanation": "The locative suffix means 'in/on/at'. It harmonizes with the last vowel of the word: -de after front vowels (e, i, ö, ü) and -da after back vowels (a, ı, o, u). After a voiceless consonant it hardens to -te/-ta.",
      "culture_note": "Vowel harmony runs through almost all Turkish suffixes — learning to hear front vs back vowels pays off everywhere.",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wiktionary: Turkish locative case",
          "url": "https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/-de"
        },
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Turkish vowel harmony",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vowel_harmony#Turkish"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "Ben {{answer}}.",
          "answer": "evdeyim",
          "translation": "I am at home.",
          "hint": "ev + -de + -(y)im",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Kitap {{answer}}.",
          "answer": "masada",
          "translation": "The book is on the table.",
          "hint": "masa + -da",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Var / yok — there is, there isn't",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Say what exists and what doesn't",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 6,
      "explanation": "'Var' asserts existence and 'yok' denies it; both come at the end: Evde süt var (There is milk at home), Parkta kimse yok (There is nobody in the park). With the locative this is also how Turkish says 'have': Bende para var (I have money, lit. 'at me money exists').",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Turkish grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turkish_grammar"
        },
        {
          "title": "Wiktionary: var (Turkish)",
          "url": "https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/var#Turkish"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "Evde süt {{answer}}.",
          "answer": "var",
          "translation": "There is milk at home.",
          "hint": "existence",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Parkta kimse {{answer}}.",
          "answer": "yok",
          "translation": "There is no one in the park.",
          "hint": "non-existence",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Possessive suffixes (-im, -in, -i…)",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Say whose something is",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 7,
      "explanation": "Possession is marked ON the possessed noun: ev-im (my house), ev-in (your house), ev-i (his/her house). The optional genitive pronoun adds emphasis: benim evim. Vowels harmonize: araba-m (my car), araban (your car).",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Turkish grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turkish_grammar"
        },
        {
