    {
      "title": "Present continuous (-iyor)",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Talk about what is happening now",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 8,
      "explanation": "The -iyor suffix marks an ongoing action ('am/is/are doing'). Its buffer vowel harmonizes (ı/i/u/ü) and a personal ending follows. For 'I', add -um: oku → okuyorum, iç → içiyorum.",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Turkish grammar — present continuous",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turkish_grammar#Present_tense"
        },
        {
          "title": "Wiktionary: -iyor (Turkish)",
          "url": "https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/-iyor#Turkish"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "Ben kitap {{answer}}.",
          "answer": "okuyorum",
          "translation": "I am reading a book.",
          "hint": "oku + -yor + -um",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "O çay {{answer}}.",
          "answer": "içiyor",
          "translation": "He/she is drinking tea.",
          "hint": "iç + -iyor",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Negative present continuous (-miyor)",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Say what is not happening",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 9,
      "explanation": "Insert the negative -m(a/e)- before -iyor; the vowel harmonizes and shrinks: iç-m-iyor-um → içmiyorum (I am not drinking), izle-m-iyor → izlemiyor (he isn't watching). The stress falls just before the negative.",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Turkish grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turkish_grammar"
        },
        {
